- What?

15:48.948 --> 15:52.384
Oh, hang on a second.
Hello?

15:52.418 --> 15:54.553
Yes, it is
Piff the Magic Dragon.

15:54.586 --> 15:56.488
Yes, I did order a pizza.

15:56.522 --> 15:59.425
Yes, Alyson is still
counting playing cards.

15:59.458 --> 16:01.327
Yes, that is you
walking on stage.

16:01.360 --> 16:02.361
Yep, keep going, Alyson.

16:02.394 --> 16:03.429
- Okay, 21.
- Off you go.

16:03.462 --> 16:05.397
- 22.
- All right, hello.

16:05.431 --> 16:06.665
Thank you very much.

16:06.699 --> 16:09.535
Hey, I got something
special for you, buddy.

16:09.568 --> 16:12.604
Oh, a crispy $20 bill.

16:12.638 --> 16:15.307
- There we go, you're welcome.
Thank you very much.

16:15.341 --> 16:16.942
- 27, elephant, elephant,
elephant.

16:16.976 --> 16:18.477
28, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:18.510 --> 16:19.611
- Mmm.
- 29.

16:19.645 --> 16:22.014
- Just the way I like it,
extra bananas.

16:22.047 --> 16:24.116
- 30--ahh!
- No pizza.

16:24.149 --> 16:25.851
- Penn, Teller,
how about a snack?

16:25.884 --> 16:28.120
It feels like we're gonna
be here quite a long time.

16:28.153 --> 16:30.789
- 32, elephant, elephant,
elephant.

16:30.823 --> 16:32.591
33, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:32.624 --> 16:34.827
34, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:34.860 --> 16:38.063
- Cheers.
- Eight--is that 38?

16:38.097 --> 16:40.599
39, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:40.632 --> 16:43.002
40, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:43.035 --> 16:45.004
42, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:45.037 --> 16:46.071
43, elephant...

16:46.105 --> 16:47.306
- We're into the final stretch.

16:47.339 --> 16:48.407
- Elephant.

16:48.440 --> 16:51.010
44, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:51.043 --> 16:54.079
45--wait, 45.

16:54.113 --> 16:55.714
- We'll do these
next ones together.

16:55.748 --> 16:56.849
- 46, elephant, elephant.

16:56.882 --> 16:58.083
- 46, elephant,
elephant, elephant.

16:58.117 --> 16:59.218
- 47.

16:59.251 --> 17:00.519
both: Elephant,
elephant, elephant.

17:00.552 --> 17:01.653
- 48.

17:01.687 --> 17:02.688
both: Elephant,
elephant, elephant.

17:02.721 --> 17:03.822
- 49.

17:03.856 --> 17:05.090
both: Elephant,
elephant, elephant.

17:05.124 --> 17:06.925
- I must have miscounted, but--

17:06.959 --> 17:08.727
- What?
- 51.

17:08.761 --> 17:10.029
I don't know,
but it's not in there.

17:10.062 --> 17:11.163
- Where's your card?
- It's not in there.

17:11.196 --> 17:12.431
- You probably just missed it.
- No.

17:12.464 --> 17:13.766
- Let's start again.

17:13.799 --> 17:15.100
Oh, you'd like that,

17:15.134 --> 17:16.602
wouldn't you, Penn and Teller,

17:16.635 --> 17:18.237
Alyson endlessly counting cards

17:18.270 --> 17:20.506
while I slowly poison myself
with potassium.

17:20.539 --> 17:22.174
Well, not on my watch

17:22.207 --> 17:24.243
because the cards were smoke
and mirrors.

17:24.276 --> 17:25.844
It's nothing to do
with the cards.

17:25.878 --> 17:27.079
It's all about the elephants.

17:27.112 --> 17:29.381
Alyson, what number
did you end up with?

17:29.415 --> 17:31.216
What number of elephants?

17:32.151 --> 17:36.088
- Uh, 153.

17:36.121 --> 17:39.992
- 153 elephants?
- Possibly.

17:40.025 --> 17:42.928
- Inside the Penn and Teller
Chamber of Sorrows,

17:42.961 --> 17:44.496
Jade, let's take a look.

17:44.530 --> 17:47.933
♪ ♪

17:47.966 --> 17:51.003
Oh, ladies and gentlemen!

17:51.036 --> 17:57.276
1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9,

17:57.309 --> 18:03.115
10, 11, 12, 13,
14, 15, 16, 17,

18:03.148 --> 18:09.288
18, 19, 20, 21,
22, 23, 24, 25,

18:09.321 --> 18:15.461
26, 27, 28, 29, 30, 31, 32,

18:15.494 --> 18:22.267
149, 150, 153 elephants!

18:22.301 --> 18:24.036
Lower the trophy!

18:24.069 --> 18:27.306
Lower the trophy!
Is there a problem?

18:27.339 --> 18:29.408
You understand
what's happening, right?

18:29.441 --> 18:32.044
You're holding
153 elephants, right?

18:32.077 --> 18:35.414
And Alyson stopped
at 153 elephants.

18:35.447 --> 18:39.218
So you understand?
Yeah?

18:39.251 --> 18:42.754
Well, guess what,
it's 152 elephants,

18:42.788 --> 18:45.591
so it's a technical fool,
but I'll take it.

18:45.624 --> 18:48.026
Ladies and gentlemen,
let's lower the trophy!

18:48.060 --> 18:50.529
Lower the trophy!

18:50.562 --> 18:51.897
Okay.

18:51.930 --> 18:53.899
You know what, I thought
it might come to this.

18:53.932 --> 18:57.002
Sure, you're holding
152 elephants.

18:57.035 --> 18:59.538
But there is still
one elephant in the room.

18:59.571 --> 19:02.908
Alyson, would you
please join me over here

19:02.941 --> 19:04.176
with the playing cards?

19:04.209 --> 19:05.577
Bring the playing cards
over here, Alyson.

19:05.611 --> 19:06.745
- All right.

19:06.778 --> 19:11.416
- That's right,
one elephant in the room.

19:11.450 --> 19:15.821
Oh, Elfie?
Oh, look who it is!

19:15.854 --> 19:19.191
it's Elfie the Magic
Performing Elephant!

19:19.224 --> 19:22.161
That's right, I've got my own
magic performing elephant,

19:22.194 --> 19:24.496
and it's not some
pigmy spotted [bleep].

19:24.530 --> 19:27.533
No, it's
a genuine baby elephant

19:27.566 --> 19:28.767
who does magic tricks.

19:28.800 --> 19:30.802
I traded in the dog
for an upgrade.

19:30.836 --> 19:32.671
All right, Alyson,
give me those playing cards.

19:32.704 --> 19:34.606
Now just focus on your card.
You ready?

19:34.640 --> 19:38.177
On the count of three.
One, two, three.

19:38.210 --> 19:40.812
Oh, would you look at that?

19:40.846 --> 19:42.948
It's the three of clubs!

19:42.981 --> 19:46.618
Give it up for Alyson,
ladies and gentlemen, Alyson!

19:46.652 --> 19:49.288
How about a round of applause
for Miss Jade Simone!

19:49.321 --> 19:51.023
- Whoo!
- Yeah!

19:51.056 --> 19:54.960
- But of course, the true star
of the evening...

19:56.995 --> 20:00.399
It's Elfie, the baby elephant!

20:00.432 --> 20:01.700
- Whoa.

20:01.733 --> 20:03.235
- Lower the trophy.

20:03.268 --> 20:07.773
Lower--you understand this is
a genuine baby elephant here.

20:07.806 --> 20:09.675
Okay.
Is this what it's come down to?

20:09.708 --> 20:12.211
Is it just gonna take
just a bribe?

20:12.244 --> 20:13.445
Is that what it's gonna be?

20:13.478 --> 20:15.380
I've been after this trophy
for ten years.

20:15.414 --> 20:19.051
So if it's about money,
then I think I can help.

20:19.084 --> 20:21.553
Jade.

20:21.587 --> 20:24.223
Alyson, that is
no regular playing card.

20:24.256 --> 20:27.192
That is in fact
a gift card, Alyson.

20:27.226 --> 20:29.361
Examine the card, Alyson.
- Yeah.

20:29.394 --> 20:32.231
- The card you're holding,
does it appear to have a lump,

20:32.264 --> 20:34.266
a bump, a lovely little hump?

20:34.299 --> 20:36.735
- It is a lovely hump.
- Yeah?

20:36.768 --> 20:37.936
- Yeah.
- But look at it.

20:37.970 --> 20:39.871
Does it look like
a standard regulation card

20:39.905 --> 20:42.374
with something growing, living,
breathing inside the card?

20:42.407 --> 20:43.642
Would you do me a favor?

20:43.675 --> 20:45.143
Would you tear the corner
of the card?

20:45.177 --> 20:46.478
Just tear the corner
of the card.

20:46.511 --> 20:47.813
Just tear the corner,
just the corner.

20:47.846 --> 20:49.147
- Okay, I hear
what you're saying.

20:49.181 --> 20:50.716
- That's it, yep,
Keep going all the way down.

20:50.749 --> 20:52.584
All the way down, keep tearing,
all the way down.

20:52.618 --> 20:54.119
- Okay, all the way.
- All the way down.

20:54.152 --> 20:56.655
- Inside Alyson's card,

20:56.688 --> 20:58.824
I believe we should find

20:58.857 --> 21:01.893
a $20 bill signed

21:01.927 --> 21:03.996
by Penn

21:04.029 --> 21:06.164
from the beginning of the show.

21:06.198 --> 21:09.201
- Wow!

21:09.234 --> 21:12.537
[laughs]

21:12.571 --> 21:16.642
Piff the Magic Dragon!

21:16.675 --> 21:18.243
Oh!

21:18.277 --> 21:20.212
That was fabulous.

21:20.245 --> 21:22.047
- Thanks, Alyson.
Thanks for your help.

21:22.080 --> 21:24.383
- Yeah, I'm so glad
I got to be a part of it.

21:24.416 --> 21:27.052
- You nailed it with the math,
didn't you?

21:27.085 --> 21:28.954
- That was the hardest part.

21:28.987 --> 21:32.691
So are you disappointed
your disguise didn't fool them?

21:32.724 --> 21:34.626
- It did fool them, clearly.
It's just--

21:34.660 --> 21:35.994
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

21:36.028 --> 21:37.362
- It would have been
the quickest fool in history.

21:37.396 --> 21:38.997
- Definitely, I mean,
for my count--and you know,

21:39.031 --> 21:40.899
the counting was the rough part
for me,

21:40.932 --> 21:43.735
but I feel like you got, like,
five or six trophies tonight.

21:43.769 --> 21:45.170
- I think so.

21:45.203 --> 21:48.206
And I could just have them
pre-packaged in one sort of,

21:48.240 --> 21:50.509
like, champagne crate,
that would be great.

21:50.542 --> 21:52.077
- Okay.

21:52.110 --> 21:54.279
What do you think
they're talking about?

21:54.313 --> 21:56.181
- Maybe how not to
break my heart.

21:56.214 --> 21:57.382
- That would be nice.

21:57.416 --> 21:59.318
Okay, Piff,
let's go to Penn and Teller

21:59.351 --> 22:04.189
and see if you get that trophy
you so desperately deserve.

22:04.222 --> 22:05.424
- Piff!

22:05.457 --> 22:06.825
- Yes.
- How are you?

22:06.858 --> 22:08.293
- I'm very good.
How are you, Penn?

22:08.327 --> 22:10.462
- Good to see you.
It's been ten years, Piff.

22:10.495 --> 22:12.998
We first met you over
in England.

22:13.031 --> 22:16.835
And since then, since your
first appearance on "Fool Us,"

22:16.868 --> 22:18.804
you've gone on
"America's Got Talent"

22:18.837 --> 22:21.373
and did fabulously,
although you didn't win.

22:21.406 --> 22:25.010
You've gotten your own theater
in Las Vegas.

22:25.043 --> 22:27.846
You've been filling it up
all the time.

22:27.879 --> 22:31.416
You play all over the country,
all over the world.

22:31.450 --> 22:33.418
You've done shows everywhere.

22:33.452 --> 22:35.721
You've accomplished so much!

22:35.754 --> 22:38.290
And the one thing
you haven't accomplished,

22:38.323 --> 22:42.494
the big drag in your life--and
I use the word "drag"

22:42.527 --> 22:45.664
very carefully--the big drag
in your life

22:45.697 --> 22:49.401
is you have not won
a "Fool Us" trophy.

22:49.434 --> 22:52.504
The first time on "Fool Us,"
you killed us.

22:52.537 --> 22:55.340
We loved you.
You did not win a trophy.

22:55.374 --> 22:58.377
During those ten years
we've been on stage together,

22:58.410 --> 23:00.779
you and I have worked here
in Vegas together,

23:00.812 --> 23:05.517
we have become really,
really close true friends,

23:05.550 --> 23:07.452
and we love you, Piff.

23:07.486 --> 23:10.856
But you did not win
a [bleep] trophy!

23:10.889 --> 23:15.627
See you in ten years!

23:15.660 --> 23:17.996
- Oh.
- You bitch.

23:18.029 --> 23:20.665
[laughter]

23:20.699 --> 23:23.535
- Piff the Magic Dragon!

23:23.568 --> 23:25.137
[cheers and applause]

23:25.170 --> 23:26.905
- Ten years, baby.
- See you in ten years, Piff.

23:26.938 --> 23:29.775
- I'll see you
in another ten, boys.

23:29.808 --> 23:31.777
- We'll also have dinner
tomorrow night, okay?

23:31.810 --> 23:33.578
- Yep, great.
I'm free.

23:33.612 --> 23:37.115
[laughter]

23:37.149 --> 23:39.084
- Penn and Teller
were surprised

23:39.117 --> 23:40.786
to see their old friend Piff.

23:40.819 --> 23:42.587
But they weren't fooled by him.

23:42.621 --> 23:45.757
More surprises to come,
so don't go anywhere.

23:45.791 --> 23:50.362
[jazz music]

23:53.665 --> 23:58.804
[jazz music]

23:58.837 --> 24:00.172
- Welcome back.

24:00.205 --> 24:02.541
Penn and Teller have already
given up more

24:02.574 --> 24:05.343
than one "Fool Us" trophy
to our next magician.

24:05.377 --> 24:07.913
Sorry, boys.
Look who's back.

24:10.115 --> 24:11.983
- When you live in Australia
and you compete

24:12.017 --> 24:14.252
against two American icons
like Penn and Teller,

24:14.286 --> 24:15.854
people take notice.

24:15.887 --> 24:18.757
Dad designs and builds
all the magic right here

24:18.790 --> 24:20.525
in his secret workshop.

24:20.559 --> 24:23.228
All our secrets are right here
in this shed.

24:23.261 --> 24:24.663
They're just
waiting to be used.

24:24.696 --> 24:26.998
We fooled
Penn and Teller once.

24:27.032 --> 24:28.800
Then we fooled them again.

24:28.834 --> 24:30.936
And then the last time
I came on...

24:30.969 --> 24:34.739
- We have a three-time Fooler,
Helen Coghlan!

24:34.773 --> 24:37.476
- I became the first magician
in history to fool

24:37.509 --> 24:39.945
Penn and Teller three times
on their own show.

24:39.978 --> 24:43.048
And it's always been
with one of Dad's tricks.

24:43.081 --> 24:45.884
We'd have to be crazy to mess
with a record like that.

24:45.917 --> 24:48.653
And with Australia's
national honor on the line,

24:48.687 --> 24:50.589
we're gonna
pull out all stops.

24:50.622 --> 24:53.558
So, Penn and Teller,
here's another one for you.

24:53.592 --> 24:55.227
♪ ♪

24:55.260 --> 24:59.231
[cheers and applause]

24:59.264 --> 25:03.568
- She's so good she doesn't
even need to be in Las Vegas

25:03.602 --> 25:05.704
to try to fool you guys.

25:05.737 --> 25:07.606
Joining from Australia

25:07.639 --> 25:11.776
is three-time Fooler
Helen Coghlan!

25:11.810 --> 25:13.578
[cheers and applause]

25:13.612 --> 25:15.180
- Hello, Penn.
Hello, Teller.

25:15.213 --> 25:16.348
I'm on the beach

25:16.381 --> 25:18.416
on the beautiful
Gold Coast, Australia.

25:18.450 --> 25:21.119
Now, I knew if I wanted to try
and fool you guys

25:21.152 --> 25:22.654
for the fourth time,

25:22.687 --> 25:25.190
I was going to have to come up
with something truly special.

25:25.223 --> 25:29.060
So Dad has created
the most difficult escape yet.

25:29.094 --> 25:31.730
I want you to be able
to see all the way around,

25:31.763 --> 25:35.166
so here's the 360-degree view.

25:35.200 --> 25:37.569
I know sometimes magicians
are known for lying.

25:37.602 --> 25:39.104
I'll admit that.

25:39.137 --> 25:41.640
But we know each other well
enough at this point, don't we?

25:41.673 --> 25:43.875
So I think you'll trust me
when I tell you

25:43.909 --> 25:46.845
that this is a 100% metal box.

25:46.878 --> 25:49.347
The bolts, they're welded
on the inside.

25:49.381 --> 25:51.983
It's completely solid
and impenetrable.

25:52.017 --> 25:55.086
The only way out is magic.

25:55.120 --> 25:58.323
All that's left to do is
attach the heavy metal door,

25:58.356 --> 26:01.693
and the solid metal latch,
and solid metal pin

26:01.726 --> 26:03.261
that's gonna seal me in tight.

26:03.295 --> 26:06.498
And I've got four volunteers
helping me out today.

26:12.671 --> 26:15.707
What makes this escape
especially difficult is

26:15.740 --> 26:17.042
that I'm barely
able to move.

26:17.075 --> 26:19.778
I'm completely trapped

26:19.811 --> 26:22.781
at my legs...

26:25.917 --> 26:28.453
My arms,
and my waist...

26:34.292 --> 26:36.094
And also my head.

26:36.127 --> 26:39.364
I've never had to escape
from anything like this before.

26:39.397 --> 26:41.266
Gee, thanks, Dad.

26:41.299 --> 26:44.636
Now, of course, I have
the home court advantage.

26:44.669 --> 26:46.304
But I like to play fair.

26:46.338 --> 26:49.641
You should have a little gift
in front of you that I've sent.

26:49.674 --> 26:51.509
Take the cover off
and have a look.

26:51.543 --> 26:54.846
It's a scale model
of the escape I'm in now.

26:54.879 --> 26:58.083
And it comes complete
with a little me inside.

26:58.116 --> 26:59.651
So if you can figure out

26:59.684 --> 27:03.355
how to get little me
out of the little cage,

27:03.388 --> 27:04.990
you'll know
how the trick's done

27:05.023 --> 27:07.459
because you know I'm not gonna
let you see me do it.

27:07.492 --> 27:10.362
After all,
we all need a little mystery.

27:10.395 --> 27:11.696
Let's do it.

27:11.730 --> 27:14.699
[tense music]

27:14.733 --> 27:21.773
♪ ♪

27:25.977 --> 27:28.513
For those of you at home trying
to figure out what I'm doing

27:28.546 --> 27:31.049
at just this moment, good luck.

27:31.082 --> 27:33.051
And to you two,
Penn and Teller,

27:33.084 --> 27:36.755
I hope this escape has you both
scratching your heads.

27:36.788 --> 27:39.224
As for why I'm on the beach,
well, that's to prove

27:39.257 --> 27:42.093
there's no trapdoor
funny business going on.

27:42.127 --> 27:44.529
Tunneling my way
out of this cage is

27:44.562 --> 27:46.598
completely
out of the question.

27:46.631 --> 27:49.267
Geez, I don't even like
getting sand in my shoes.

27:49.300 --> 27:50.869
And the last thing I want is

27:50.902 --> 27:52.937
to be buried headfirst
under it

27:52.971 --> 27:56.408
with a 300-pound steel cage
on top of me.

27:56.441 --> 27:58.810
But hang on,
I don't need a trap door.

27:58.843 --> 28:01.446
I think I've got
this figured out.

28:01.479 --> 28:03.248
Penn, Teller,

28:03.281 --> 28:05.617
you'll see the cage is
still completely locked,

28:05.650 --> 28:08.453
and the restraining shelves
are still in place.

28:08.486 --> 28:10.989
It's as if I've walked
through solid steel.

28:11.022 --> 28:12.724
And maybe I did.

28:12.757 --> 28:18.363
[cheers and applause]

28:18.396 --> 28:20.865
- Helen Coghlan!

28:20.899 --> 28:22.634
[cheers and applause]

28:22.667 --> 28:26.071
Hi, I miss you!

28:26.104 --> 28:28.440
- Hi, Alyson.
I've missed you as well.

28:28.473 --> 28:30.408
- So fooling them three times.

28:30.442 --> 28:33.445
You must be a hero
in Australia.

28:33.478 --> 28:37.348
- I wouldn't go that far.
I haven't saved anyone.

28:37.382 --> 28:40.852
But I'm quite excited
about the third trophy.

28:40.885 --> 28:42.754
And obviously, Dad is as well.

28:42.787 --> 28:45.490
- Yeah, is it fun to be working
with your dad,

28:45.523 --> 28:47.258
or is he a tough partner?

28:47.292 --> 28:48.293
- It's fantastic.

28:48.326 --> 28:49.694
It really is good.
I love it.

28:49.728 --> 28:52.263
- Do you think
you've fooled them again?

28:52.297 --> 28:54.733
- Honestly, Alyson,
I couldn't say.

28:54.766 --> 28:58.236
But I'm really--I'm
hoping I have.

28:58.269 --> 28:59.838
- Okay, Helen, let's see

28:59.871 --> 29:03.975
if you can escape
with a fourth trophy.

29:04.008 --> 29:06.611
- Hello, Helen.

29:06.644 --> 29:08.480
- Hello, Penn.
Hello, Teller.

29:08.513 --> 29:10.749
- Here we are again.
- Have you missed me?

29:10.782 --> 29:15.019
- You know, you and your dad
work on these things.

29:15.053 --> 29:17.055
You prepare yourself for these.

29:17.088 --> 29:19.991
But this time,
we prepared for you

29:20.024 --> 29:21.426
because Teller,
unbeknownst to you...

29:21.459 --> 29:22.494
- Ooh, okay.

29:22.527 --> 29:24.629
- He bought your dad's book.

29:24.662 --> 29:26.865
- Uh-oh.
- He bought your dad's book.

29:26.898 --> 29:29.434
And he studied it.
And he read it.

29:29.467 --> 29:34.139
And he came down with--thinking
about the way

29:34.172 --> 29:37.709
you've done stuff in the past,
the way your dad does stuff,

29:37.742 --> 29:41.813
he had a way with hinges
and stuff like that,

29:41.846 --> 29:46.518
but he didn't have every single
detail on how you get out that.

29:46.551 --> 29:49.120
I thought--and I couldn't

29:49.154 --> 29:51.222
figure out exactly
how to do it,

29:51.256 --> 29:54.259
but I thought
that the whole front was

29:54.292 --> 29:55.827
all just misdirection,

29:55.860 --> 29:57.762
and you actually
went out the back.

29:57.796 --> 29:59.330
We don't get two bites
at the apple,

29:59.364 --> 30:00.532
so we had to pick one.

30:00.565 --> 30:03.535
So since Teller didn't have
all the details,

30:03.568 --> 30:05.537
and I didn't have
all the details,

30:05.570 --> 30:08.373
we decided to come down
to one question.

30:08.406 --> 30:10.708
And that is--we're just,

30:10.742 --> 30:12.610
you know,
holding you to your word.

30:12.644 --> 30:14.879
You're out on a beach
in Australia.

30:14.913 --> 30:17.782
We're back here in Vegas.

30:17.816 --> 30:19.584
Did you go out the back?

30:19.617 --> 30:20.919
That's all we're giving you.

30:20.952 --> 30:22.153
If you went out the back,

30:22.187 --> 30:23.955
you don't get
your fourth trophy,

30:23.988 --> 30:25.590
and we win this time.

30:25.623 --> 30:28.793
Did you go out the back, Helen?

30:28.827 --> 30:31.095
- Start lowering
that trophy, boys.

30:31.129 --> 30:32.297
- Oh!
- Yay!

30:32.330 --> 30:34.933
- I did not go out the back.
- Whoo!

30:34.966 --> 30:36.201
- Four times, Helen!

30:36.234 --> 30:38.670
- We have a four-time Fooler!
- Four times.

30:38.703 --> 30:40.872
- Fool me once,
well, never mind.

30:40.905 --> 30:43.708
Fool me four times,
it's shame on everybody.

30:43.741 --> 30:46.878
But next time,
you're not gonna fool us.

30:46.911 --> 30:48.346
We're gonna prepare even more.
- That's a challenge.

30:48.379 --> 30:50.081
That's a challenge.
- That is a challenge.

30:50.114 --> 30:52.650
- We have another
four-time Fooler!

30:52.684 --> 30:55.019
Congratulations, Helen Coghlan.

30:55.053 --> 30:57.956
Penn and Teller will keep
your trophy tucked away

30:57.989 --> 31:00.024
until you join them in Vegas.

31:00.058 --> 31:01.492
Yay!

31:01.526 --> 31:03.228
- Say hi to Australia
for us, Helen.

31:03.261 --> 31:04.562
Love you.
Peace.

31:04.596 --> 31:06.664
- Bye.
- Bye.

31:06.698 --> 31:08.766
[cheers and applause]

31:08.800 --> 31:10.635
We've got a Fooler
in the house.

31:10.668 --> 31:12.537
And we could have another.

31:12.570 --> 31:14.706
More "Fool Us" after this.

31:14.739 --> 31:19.310
[jazz music]

31:24.682 --> 31:27.819
♪ ♪

31:27.852 --> 31:29.220
- Welcome back.

31:29.254 --> 31:32.323
This next magician
already has a "Fool Us" trophy,

31:32.357 --> 31:35.860
but he wants to mess with
Penn and Teller one more time.

31:35.894 --> 31:36.995
Take a look.

31:39.330 --> 31:41.232
- Surprise.
I'm back again.

31:41.266 --> 31:42.700
- Paul Gertner!

31:42.734 --> 31:44.269
- For those that
are keeping score,

31:44.302 --> 31:46.671
I've been on "Fool Us"
four times.

31:46.704 --> 31:49.007
I'm pretty sure
that's a "Fool Us" record.

31:49.040 --> 31:52.110
And I've fooled
Penn and Teller twice.

31:52.143 --> 31:54.612
My wife Catherine
gets really nervous

31:54.646 --> 31:56.281
when she watches me perform.

31:56.314 --> 31:59.417
After my last appearance,
I promised her I'm done.

31:59.450 --> 32:01.619
I won't be back
on "Fool Us" again.

32:01.653 --> 32:05.890
But then, I thought of a new
trick, and it's a good one.

32:05.924 --> 32:08.826
My show in Boston
is my testing ground.

32:08.860 --> 32:10.428
Every trick I do here,

32:10.461 --> 32:12.630
I've done there
hundreds of times.

32:12.664 --> 32:14.666
But I haven't been
doing shows lately,

32:14.699 --> 32:16.901
so I'll be facing
Penn and Teller

32:16.935 --> 32:18.703
with a trick I think
will work,

32:18.736 --> 32:20.438
but it's a little scary.

32:20.471 --> 32:23.741
Catherine, I'm sorry,
but this is the last time.

32:23.775 --> 32:25.410
And we'll finally see
how I make out

32:25.443 --> 32:27.312
in this best of five series.

32:27.345 --> 32:30.415
It's tied two-to-two.
Cross your fingers.

32:31.115 --> 32:34.819
[cheers and applause]

32:34.852 --> 32:38.723
- Making his record-breaking
fifth appearance on "Fool Us,"

32:38.756 --> 32:41.926
please welcome Paul Gertner!

32:41.960 --> 32:44.295
- Thank you, thank you.

32:44.329 --> 32:46.164
Well, Penn, Teller,
it is a pleasure

32:46.197 --> 32:48.232
to be back here
on "Fool Us" again.

32:48.266 --> 32:49.767
And I realized,

32:49.801 --> 32:53.738
since I'm going for my third
"Fool Us" trophy,

32:53.771 --> 32:58.009
tonight I have
to perform a hat trick.

32:58.042 --> 32:59.277
- Yeah.

32:59.310 --> 33:01.379
- And it's a very simple trick.

33:01.412 --> 33:03.548
It uses three objects.

33:03.581 --> 33:07.018
It uses three dice, a hat,

33:07.051 --> 33:09.887
and it uses a magic wand.

33:09.921 --> 33:11.956
Now, the dice will stay here

33:11.990 --> 33:13.958
on the table by Penn.

33:13.992 --> 33:16.995
The hat will stay over here
on the table by Teller.

33:17.028 --> 33:19.964
And the wand is going
to stay in my hand.

33:19.998 --> 33:21.733
And if you
watch the three dice,

33:21.766 --> 33:23.234
I'll take them one at a time.

33:23.267 --> 33:26.170
Die number one,
I take it in the hand,

33:26.204 --> 33:27.705
I give it a tap,

33:27.739 --> 33:31.576
and it disappears,
and travels through the air,

33:31.609 --> 33:34.012
across the table,
over by Teller,

33:34.045 --> 33:36.280
under the hat.

33:36.314 --> 33:38.549
Now, that's the first time.

33:38.583 --> 33:40.051
I'll do it again.

33:40.084 --> 33:43.021
See, if you watch die
number two, and, Penn,

33:43.054 --> 33:45.523
if you watch very carefully,
I'm gonna place it in my hand.

33:45.556 --> 33:47.658
I'll ask you a question.
You can be honest.

33:47.692 --> 33:49.227
You're not gonna
hurt my feelings.

33:49.260 --> 33:51.029
Do you think it's still there?
Or you think it's gone already?

33:51.062 --> 33:53.031
- I think it's in the hand.
- You're right.

33:53.064 --> 33:55.767
I didn't do anything yet,
but this is die number two,

33:55.800 --> 33:58.970
which means I have
to tap it twice.

33:59.003 --> 34:00.972
And then it disappears,

34:01.005 --> 34:03.574
travels through the air,
across the table,

34:03.608 --> 34:06.577
over by Teller, under the hat.

34:06.611 --> 34:09.747
Now, I'll do it one more time,
but this time, Teller,

34:09.781 --> 34:12.583
I'm going to reveal part
of the secret to the trick,

34:12.617 --> 34:14.952
not the whole secret,
just part of the secret.

34:14.986 --> 34:17.155
You see, when I pick up the die

34:17.188 --> 34:18.756
and I place it in my hand,

34:18.790 --> 34:21.359
it only stays here
for a few seconds.

34:21.392 --> 34:24.228
And when I tap it,
I don't just tap it,

34:24.262 --> 34:26.931
I give it what we call
in the trade a tap and take.

34:26.964 --> 34:28.900
You're familiar with that,
of course.

34:28.933 --> 34:30.768
It's something magicians use
all the time.

34:30.802 --> 34:34.138
You see, I tap and take it
at the same time.

34:34.172 --> 34:35.673
Now, let me explain.

34:35.706 --> 34:38.409
When I did this the first
few times, you didn't see it,

34:38.443 --> 34:40.445
because my hands were
moving so fast,

34:40.478 --> 34:42.680
even if you watched this
in slow-motion video,

34:42.713 --> 34:45.550
you wouldn't see the tap
and take done at fast speed.

34:45.583 --> 34:47.685
But watch what happens
when I slow down the process.

34:47.718 --> 34:50.955
You can see the tap
and the take separated

34:50.988 --> 34:52.523
by about half a second.

34:52.557 --> 34:55.126
I take it from here
over to here.

34:55.159 --> 34:57.361
I pretend to place it
in my pocket.

34:57.395 --> 35:00.465
But of course, in reality,
I'm going to take this die,

35:00.498 --> 35:02.733
and I'm going to flick it
under the hat,

35:02.767 --> 35:05.570
and it looks like
it was there all the while.

35:05.603 --> 35:07.805
Now, we'll do it one
last time, though.

35:07.839 --> 35:10.174
You see, if I take two
in the hand,

35:10.208 --> 35:13.077
one in the pocket--Penn,
how many in the hand?

35:13.111 --> 35:15.213
- Two.

35:15.246 --> 35:17.582
- But if I give it a tap,
there's one, two, three.

35:17.615 --> 35:19.784
I'll do it again,
here, Teller, so you can see.

35:19.817 --> 35:22.954
Two in the hand,
one stays in the pocket.

35:22.987 --> 35:24.355
Yeah.

35:24.388 --> 35:26.157
But if I give it a tap,

35:26.190 --> 35:28.693
now there's one,
two, and three.

35:28.726 --> 35:31.362
Penn, Teller,
this is your last chance

35:31.395 --> 35:34.365
to see how they get
in the pocket or the hand.

35:34.398 --> 35:36.901
Slow-motion.
That's one.

35:36.934 --> 35:38.102
That's two.

35:38.136 --> 35:40.004
This one stays in the pocket.

35:40.037 --> 35:43.708
And Penn, if you watch
very closely, take a guess.

35:43.741 --> 35:45.109
Where do you think
the dice are?

35:45.143 --> 35:47.178
♪ ♪

35:47.211 --> 35:48.913
- In the hat.
- The hat?

35:48.946 --> 35:51.482
You know, those three dice
have combined under the hat

35:51.516 --> 35:55.419
to form--let me
check--yep, the big one.

35:55.453 --> 35:57.622
Hey, but I know where
this one comes from.

35:57.655 --> 36:00.224
And I know where
this one comes from.

36:00.258 --> 36:02.326
But you know what
I can't figure out?

36:02.360 --> 36:04.262
♪ ♪

36:04.295 --> 36:08.533
Where in the world did that
one come from?

36:08.566 --> 36:09.767
Thank you.

36:09.800 --> 36:11.736
Hey, I don't know
if these two surprised you.

36:11.769 --> 36:15.740
But I'm kind of hoping
this one this one will

36:15.773 --> 36:17.975
because we're in Las Vegas.

36:18.009 --> 36:21.412
And in Las Vegas,
dice always come

36:21.445 --> 36:24.749
in pairs.

36:24.782 --> 36:27.285
Hey, Penn, Teller, I just
produced three jumbo dice,

36:27.318 --> 36:31.222
but that's not the hat trick
I promised.

36:31.255 --> 36:35.193
This is the hat trick.

36:35.226 --> 36:36.727
- Very nice.

36:36.761 --> 36:38.729
- And Penn, you get the hat.

36:38.763 --> 36:40.598
Teller, you get the die.

36:40.631 --> 36:42.533
And I thank you very much.

36:42.567 --> 36:44.235
- Thank you so much.
- Thank you!

36:44.268 --> 36:46.103
Thank you.

36:46.137 --> 36:48.072
- Paul Gertner!

36:48.105 --> 36:51.676
[cheers and applause]

36:51.709 --> 36:54.912
I mean,
this is your fifth time here.

36:54.946 --> 36:57.848
And so far, you fool them
every other time.

36:57.882 --> 36:59.584
- That's true.
I have every other time.

36:59.617 --> 37:01.018
- Yeah.
- You're right, you're right.

37:01.052 --> 37:02.987
- Is this a trick
they'd be familiar with?

37:03.020 --> 37:05.022
- Well, actually,
I've been doing the bulk

37:05.056 --> 37:06.824
of the trick
for about 40 years.

37:06.857 --> 37:07.992
But that ending,

37:08.025 --> 37:09.994
it's the premiere here
for that ending.

37:10.027 --> 37:11.429
- Oh, my goodness.

37:11.462 --> 37:14.131
Do you try to get
into their headspace of, like,

37:14.165 --> 37:15.600
what are they gonna
be looking for?

37:15.633 --> 37:16.601
- Completely.
- Oh.

37:16.634 --> 37:17.868
- Completely, yeah.

37:17.902 --> 37:19.904
There's a number of elements

37:19.937 --> 37:22.006
designed in this trick
just for that purpose.

37:22.039 --> 37:24.609
- So do they have a blind spot?

37:24.642 --> 37:26.944
- Hmm, that's a good question.

37:26.978 --> 37:28.879
'Cause I don't know,
but I'm hoping I found it.

37:28.913 --> 37:30.615
- Yeah, all right,
Paul, well,

37:30.648 --> 37:32.984
let's see if your hat trick
gives you a hat trick.

37:33.017 --> 37:34.885
- Okay.

37:34.919 --> 37:36.787
- Hey, Paul, we love having you
on the show,

37:36.821 --> 37:38.022
for all sorts of reasons.

37:38.055 --> 37:39.790
First of all, we love you,
and you're great.

37:39.824 --> 37:42.860
But also, even if you do
classic stuff,

37:42.893 --> 37:45.363
you do it better
than anyone else.

37:45.396 --> 37:47.665
And for anybody
who's studying magic,

37:47.698 --> 37:50.268
you got a ball routine here,

37:50.301 --> 37:52.436
you've got two in the hand,
one in the pocket,

37:52.470 --> 37:56.807
you've got a Max Malini
big ending with big things.

37:56.841 --> 38:01.812
And a lot of people are very,
very happy to do one big finish

38:01.846 --> 38:03.414
or two big finishes,

38:03.447 --> 38:07.618
or rarely three,
but you did, like--all nested,

38:07.652 --> 38:09.654
one in the other, like four.

38:09.687 --> 38:12.089
And then if you add
all the dice together, you did,

38:12.123 --> 38:13.824
like, dozens,

38:13.858 --> 38:15.426
maybe a hundred
big endings there.

38:15.459 --> 38:16.794
It's really great.

38:16.827 --> 38:19.764
And when you fool us,
I always get a little angry,

38:19.797 --> 38:22.633
and I've called you
a lot of things, Paul,

38:22.667 --> 38:26.304
not all to your face,
some to Teller here.

38:26.337 --> 38:29.573
But the one we haven't
called you is a cockroach.

38:29.607 --> 38:31.609
I've never called you
a cockroach.

38:31.642 --> 38:33.844
But I wanted
to call you a cockroach.

38:33.878 --> 38:38.149
It reminded us of when we were
on David Letterman's program.

38:38.182 --> 38:40.284
And on David Letterman's
program,

38:40.318 --> 38:43.554
we had a top hat that we
brought away from the desk

38:43.587 --> 38:46.424
and then put back on the desk,
and then opened it up,

38:46.457 --> 38:48.392
and it had--or pulled it
off--and it had,

38:48.426 --> 38:52.396
like, hundreds,
hundreds of cockroaches.

38:52.430 --> 38:53.397
- Ew.

38:53.431 --> 38:54.565
- And I think the way

38:54.598 --> 38:57.068
we loaded
those final cockroaches

38:57.101 --> 39:00.204
was very similar to the way
you did the dice there.

39:00.237 --> 39:03.274
And when I did all the
cockroaches on David Letterman,

39:03.307 --> 39:04.942
and they covered
David Letterman,

39:04.975 --> 39:08.979
I called my mother
and told her what we had done

39:09.013 --> 39:11.215
to David Letterman,
and she said to me,

39:11.248 --> 39:14.618
"You will never work
in show business again.

39:14.652 --> 39:16.721
You'll never be
on that show again."

39:16.754 --> 39:20.725
And I want to say to you, Paul,
I don't think you fooled us,

39:20.758 --> 39:23.661
but I really, really hope
you're on this show

39:23.694 --> 39:26.163
a lot more in the future.

39:26.197 --> 39:28.099
- Well...
- Well?

39:28.132 --> 39:32.203
- I think you definitely nailed
that cockroach thing.

39:32.236 --> 39:34.638
- Aww, so they know
how you did the trick?

39:34.672 --> 39:35.906
- I think they got me.

39:35.940 --> 39:37.341
- Aww.

39:37.375 --> 39:41.045
Well, Paul,
we love you so much.

39:41.078 --> 39:42.546
Paul Gertner!

39:42.580 --> 39:44.615
- Thank you!

39:44.648 --> 39:46.550
- Thanks, Paul.

39:46.584 --> 39:48.853
[cheers and applause]

39:48.886 --> 39:51.122
- Stay right where you are
because up next,

39:51.155 --> 39:53.958
it's time for Penn and Teller
to take center stage

39:53.991 --> 39:55.860
with a trick of their own.

39:55.893 --> 40:00.398
[jazz music]

40:03.701 --> 40:07.338
[jazz music]

40:07.371 --> 40:09.373
- We couldn't say goodbye
without seeing

40:09.407 --> 40:12.376
a signature trick
from our amazing duo.

40:12.410 --> 40:14.111
Take it away, Penn and Teller.

40:14.145 --> 40:15.946
- Stay right here, Alyson.
I want to show you something.

40:15.980 --> 40:18.582
You know, there's still
some people that have trouble

40:18.616 --> 40:20.918
accepting evolution as fact.

40:20.951 --> 40:22.953
I think their problem is
they can't imagine--no matter

40:22.987 --> 40:25.289
what the time period
is--one species

40:25.322 --> 40:26.624
turning into another.

40:26.657 --> 40:29.860
But I am uniquely gifted
to give them a demonstration

40:29.894 --> 40:31.562
how that can happen
'cause I can turn

40:31.595 --> 40:32.797
from this species into another.

40:32.830 --> 40:34.131
Let me show you.

40:34.165 --> 40:35.966
Step over there on the other
side of my gorillas gas.

40:36.000 --> 40:37.568
Teller created
this gorilla gas,

40:37.601 --> 40:39.837
which helps my DNA reformulate.

40:39.870 --> 40:41.038
I just have
to take a hit of it,

40:41.071 --> 40:43.908
and already I start to change.

40:43.941 --> 40:45.576
See, Alyson,
already I feel different.

40:45.609 --> 40:47.611
And--ahh!
I'm turning into a gorilla.

40:47.645 --> 40:49.513
The species is
actually changing.

40:49.547 --> 40:50.848
But I don't want
to hurt you, Alyson.

40:50.881 --> 40:52.616
And I will
as I become more animal.

40:52.650 --> 40:55.419
So lock me in this cage.
Lock me in this cage, Alyson.

40:55.453 --> 40:57.087
I don't want to hurt you,
but I will.

40:57.121 --> 40:58.189
Lock it,
and then go in the chair.

40:58.222 --> 40:59.557
- Okay.
- Alyson, go in the chair.

40:59.590 --> 41:00.925
- Okay, okay, I'm trying!
- Protect yourself, Alyson!

41:00.958 --> 41:02.026
- I'm trying!
- Protect yourself!

41:02.059 --> 41:03.427
- Okay!
- Better go--I'm changing!

41:03.461 --> 41:04.862
I'm changing!
Teller, the drums!

41:04.895 --> 41:07.498
Teller, the drums!
